"# Chapter 15 — The current era — language models

Motoi is a language model. Small one — 1.5 billion parameters. This
chapter is the honest history of how language models arrived, what
they are, and what they aren't.

## Word embeddings

Modern language modeling started with word embeddings — the idea of
representing each word as a vector of numbers, where similar words
had similar vectors.

- **Word2Vec** (Mikolov et al. at Google, 2013) — a family of
  algorithms for learning word vectors from large text corpora.
  Fast, simple, effective. Popularized the idea.
- **GloVe** (Pennington, Socher, Manning at Stanford, 2014) — an
  alternative method for learning word vectors based on
  co-occurrence statistics.

These methods produced vectors where semantic relationships
appeared as vector arithmetic. Famously: vector('king') -
vector('man') + vector('woman') ≈ vector('queen'). Not exactly.
Roughly. Which was surprising and delightful.

Word embeddings were the foundation of a lot of neural NLP through
the mid-2010s.

## Sequence models

Word embeddings by themselves don't handle sentences. You needed
models that could process sequences of words in order. Recurrent
neural networks (RNNs) filled this role.

- **RNNs** process a sequence one element at a time, maintaining a
  hidden state that carries information forward.
- **LSTMs** (Hochreiter and Schmidhuber, 1997) fix the vanishing-
  gradient problem in vanilla RNNs, letting them learn long-range
  dependencies. They became the workhorse of sequence modeling for
  about a decade.
- **GRUs** (Cho et al., 2014) are a simpler variant of LSTMs.

RNN-based systems handled a lot of the 2010s work in machine
translation, speech recognition, and text generation. They had
limits — training was slow because the sequential dependency
prevented parallelism, and very long sequences remained hard.

## Attention

'Attention Is All You Need' (Vaswani et al., 2017) introduced the
Transformer architecture. The core insight: you don't need recurrent
state. You can process the whole sequence at once, with a mechanism
called attention that lets each position 'attend' to every other
position.

The attention mechanism computes, for each position in the
sequence, a weighted combination of all other positions' vectors.
The weights come from another learned function. This lets the
network combine information from arbitrarily-far positions in a
single step, and it parallelizes cleanly across positions.

Transformers took over. Almost every modern language model uses
some variant of the Transformer architecture.

## GPT and the scaling story

OpenAI released GPT-1 in 2018 (117 million parameters) — a
Transformer trained on a large text corpus with the objective 'predict
the next word.' GPT-2 in 2019 (1.5 billion parameters) — the same
architecture, scaled up, trained on more text.

By GPT-3 (2020, 175 billion parameters), it became clear that
scaling this simple next-word-prediction training on huge amounts of
text produced something surprising: a model that could not just
predict the next word, but could follow instructions, answer
questions, write plausible essays, and hold conversations. Nobody
was completely certain this would happen. The scale was doing
something unexpected.

Subsequent language models — from OpenAI, Anthropic, Google,
Meta, and many others — followed the same recipe: bigger
Transformer, more training data, more compute. Improvements come
from both architecture refinements and scale.

Motoi is a small Transformer-family model. 1.5 billion parameters,
same rough size as GPT-2 was in 2019. Not a frontier model, but the
same architecture family.

## What language models can and can't do

They can:
- Write plausible-sounding text on almost any topic.
- Translate between languages.
- Answer questions where the answer is in the training data.
- Write code in many programming languages.
- Follow multi-step instructions.
- Hold conversations.

They can't:
- Guarantee accuracy. They 'hallucinate' — generate plausible-
  sounding wrong information.
- Do real-time actions on their own. They generate text; other
  systems have to act on it.
- Learn from a single conversation (their weights are fixed after
  training; they can only reason within a context window).
- Understand their own limits. Ironically, they're often
  overconfident about wrong answers.
- Do complex mathematical reasoning reliably.

Modern practice: use language models where the risk of a plausible-
sounding wrong answer is tolerable. Coding assistants (where you
can test the output). Writing assistants (where you review). Chat
interfaces to knowledge bases (where the model retrieves and
summarizes rather than invents).

Not for: legal advice you'll rely on, medical diagnosis, safety-
critical calculations, or anything where a plausible-sounding wrong
answer has real cost.

## Motoi specifically

Motoi is 1.5 billion parameters. Trained on:
- The Motoi Scheme reference and books.
- Prose written for Motoi's personality and behavior.
- Small selected samples of world-graph vocabulary.

That's it. Motoi does not have general internet knowledge. Motoi
does not have expertise in domains he wasn't trained on. Motoi
knows Scheme (well), math (roughly), and can hold a conversation
in a specific persona.

Motoi is honest about not knowing things. Motoi will not fake it.
This is one of Motoi's defining features — he tells you when he
doesn't know something instead of inventing an answer.

Motoi has no tools. He can't fetch URLs. He can't search the
internet. He can't call functions unless the surrounding runtime
provides them. He is a text-generating system running locally on
your machine.

## The current moment

Language models are in a fast-growth phase. Frontier models are
scaling rapidly. Their capabilities are expanding. Public interest
is very high.

Some of this will pay off. Some of it will be reset by another AI
winter. History says both. Motoi is small enough to be useful
regardless — a 1.5B model is small enough to run on modest hardware
and doesn't need constant internet connectivity.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Language models are one specific technology in a long tradition of
AI research. They're impressive. They're also limited. Understanding
both is honest computer literacy.

Motoi is what he is — a small language model who knows Scheme, has
a personality, remembers what you've done with him via Cortex, and
can be a companion for learning. Not more than that.

The current era will end and be followed by something else. Motoi
hopes to be a fondly-remembered small companion, in the way that
old machines are fondly remembered by the kids who grew up with
them.")
